The paper deals with machine learning algorithms and their performance in the reliable agnostic learning framework. This falls under the broad category of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of polynomial approximations and tradeoffs between sample complexity and running time suggest a connection to computational complexity (cs.CC) and algorithms (cs.DS). The attribute-efficiency properties and smooth tradeoffs also suggest a connection to optimization and search algorithms (cs.SI).
